Text: The project involves two pillars of development in parallel - the first is the data science aspect.
That means exploring clustering algorithms that would work best with the given plastination image.
The second is the user interface aspect - incorporating tools to help the user manipulate and fine tune the algorithm manually.

I wanted to be involved in both aspects - so, I spent last week researching and clueing up on the QuickShift Superpixelling algorithm and navigating Toto's current UI script and attempting to help him add functionalities to the buttons.
How did I go with that, you ask?
Well, in terms of the UI, I got as far as adding a functional 'upload image' button.
I felt that it was very challenging trying to write code for something I did not completely understand.
For the entirety of the week - I spent the majority of my time researching how to create a 'graphical user interface' with Python.
There is still much more learning to go - but I am enjoying the process.
What I need to do differently this week is essentially giving myself a set timeframe to work on the tasks delegated to myself.
I sometimes feel I do too many things at once - which can result in not completing as much as I would like.
Not ideal at all.
Thus far, I feel that the team dynamic is going swimmingly.
We laid out our team rules on Monday and these involve:  Transparency, Collaboration (making decisions together), Respect (eg. letting the team know if you can't make a meeting) and Have Fun.
The team and I had an end-of-week team reflection meeting on Friday.
It was important to do so because I feel that is important to get everyone's stance on the week.
We discussed and reflected on the things we could improve on, what has gone well so far, the tasks to be completed and tasks delegation for next week.

Overall, the needed improvements involve 1) getting in touch with Jeremiah more, perhaps posting screenshots in our Microsoft teams chat often - getting frequent feedback so we know that we know we are on the same page as the client.
This is especially because we also feel that we only have a high level understanding of the project.
2) Create a proper project task list:  This would allow more structure in the project and would allow for smoother project progression.
Use of trello more frequently or have quality in-person meetings would be good solutions.

3) Establish proper user stories and taking a top down approach:  when we get to meet with the anatomy department, understand their segmentation process and get them to describe the features that would 'must-have' in the desktop app.
We shall first develop a couple of low fidelity prototypes to take to them and ask for feedback and develop the app based on the required functionalities.
In contrast, what has gone well so far is the division of tasks.
We feel that everyone's productivity level is good and no one is feeling left out.
That everyone is on the same page and everyone has great communication and initiative.
In terms of task delegation - we created a list of things to be completed and everyone essentially chose a task they would like to work on.
This week I have a role in a couple of tasks:  1) developing a few low fidelity prototypes of the UI by researching user experiences.
This will be done in collaboration with Koko.
2) I will incorporate the superpixelling algorithm with the user uploaded image.
Toto has so far incorporated the superpixelling with a hard-coded image, but I am needing to make the code more flexible.
Let's see how we go ðŸ˜…
